    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-08-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-08-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="402"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d402">
                <head>402. Memorandum From the Chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MCPW1" type="from">McCracken</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d402fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, White House
                        Central Files, <persName corresp="#p_HH1">Houthakker</persName>, Box 19,
                        Wheat-Wheat Pricing. No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-08-05">August 5, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>The International Wheat Situation and Its Domestic Implications</item>
                </list>
                <p>The wheat situation continues to be very unsettled. The <gloss target="#t_EEC1"
                        >EEC</gloss> reduced some of its export prices in retaliation for our cut of
                    July 18, but the European cut was not as deep or as extensive as we expected. On
                    Friday and Saturday the five leading exporters, (the U.S., the <gloss
                        target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss>, Canada, Australia and Argentina) met in
                    London. Although little concrete progress was made the atmosphere was good and
                    press talk of a “price war” is premature. Another meeting is scheduled for
                    August 11.</p>
                <p>Behind the apparent calm the danger of a major confrontation with the <gloss
                        target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> and of friction with Canada, Australia, Japan
                    and Brazil remains as real as ever. We have sold little if any wheat for several
                    weeks now, which increases the impatience of the U.S. Department of Agriculture
                    to make further cuts. Since the other exporters would undoubtedly follow us
                    down, it is not clear that we would sell any more wheat as a result. The <gloss
                        target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> would have further evidence for its accusation
                    that we are bent on wrecking the International Grains Agreement, and we would
                    lose the support of Canada and Australia. On the other hand Japan and Brazil,
                    both major importers, are complaining that we have reduced prices to Europe but
                    not to them.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_IGA1">IGA</gloss> crisis is also beginning to have domestic
                    repercussions. Senator McGovern last week urged the Administration to uphold the
                    agreement; Senator Mansfield is reported to be of the same opinion. The
                    announcement of the 1970 wheat program is already overdue; it will undoubtedly
                    generate more heat.</p>
                <p>The interagency Task Force on Agricultural Trade is preparing an options paper
                    for the Cabinet Committee on Economic Policy.<note n="2" xml:id="d402fn2">The
                        Cabinet Committee on Economic Policy took up the issue on August 12; see
                            <ref target="#d403">Document 403</ref>.</note> Pending a consensus on
                    this matter it would be highly undesirable to cut wheat prices any further. If
                    you agree, I suggest that Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HCM1"
                        >Hardin</persName> be informed of this.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MCPW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Paul W. McCracken</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
